
[1]marble

   M`ARBLE, n. [L. marmor; Gr. white.]

   1. The popular name of any species of calcarious stone or mineral, of a
   compact texture, and of a beautiful appearance, susceptible of a good
   polish. The varieties are numerous, and greatly diversified in color.
   Marble is limestone, or a stone which may be calcined to lime, a
   carbonate of lime; but limestone is a more general name, comprehending
   the calcarious stones of an inferior texture, as well as those which
   admit a fine polish. Marble is much used for statues, busts, pillars,
   chimney pieces, monuments, &c.

   2. A little ball of marble or other stone,used by children in play.

   3. A stone remarkable for some inscription or sculpture.

                              Arundel marbles,

      Arundelian marbles, marble pieces with a chronicle of the city of
     Athens inscribed on them; presented to the university of Oxford, by
                          Thomas, earl of Arundel.

               M`ARBLE, a. Made of marble; as a marble pillar.
